  "summary": "Following a conversation with Misty, where the narrator attempts to address her perceived isolation and the destiny of the Tsubaki family, Misty leaves in a state of distress. The narrator then considers the problem of when Maria will ascend to heaven.\n\nIn a new chapter, the narrator speaks with Mutsuji (Muto), who is preoccupied with playing with a needle. They discuss a threatening letter sent three days ago. The narrator notes that because there is no local post office, the sender must have traveled to mail it. Mutsuji identifies that besides the staff, only Yutaka and Kouji have left the area. Since the letter had to be sent shortly after one from Itou, and only Jouma, Sugai, Yutaka, and Kouji can drive, the narrator narrows the suspects to Jouma or Sugai. Mutsuji, however, views the letter as a \"bottleneck\" rather than a simple clue and keeps his specific hypothesis as an \"ace card\" from the Inspector.\n\nLater, the narrator encounters a haggard and agitated Jinma (Shizuma) in the hall. Jinma criticizes the narrator's leisure following the death of Aunt Cui and Aaru. The narrator observes that Jinma’s usual arrogance has been replaced by a fearful bravado. In a subsequent discussion with Muto, the narrator reflects on fate, comparing themselves to the goddesses Clotho and Atropos. Muto rejects the concept of fate, suggesting that only \"Death\" lurks in the mansion. The passage concludes with Muto revealing that Jinma loves Yuyan, suggesting that the narrator's fatalistic views might overlook more positive underlying truths.",
